  "prompt": "Which is stronger acid, HClO4 or HIO4? And why?",
  "response": "HClO4 (perchloric acid) is stronger than HIO4 (periodic acid). \n\nThe strength of oxyacids, such as HClO4 and HIO4, can generally be understood by considering the electronegativity of the central atom and the number of oxygen atoms attached to that atom. \n\n1. **Electronegativity of the Central Atom:** Chlorine is more electronegative than iodine. A more electronegative central atom can withdraw electron density through the inductive effect, which stabilizes the conjugate base (ClO4^- compared to IO4^-). This stabilization makes the parent acid stronger since it more readily donates a proton.\n\n2. **Oxygen Atom Comparison:** Both HClO4 and HIO4 have four oxygen atoms, which contributes to the same extent in terms of additional electron-withdrawing effects and resonance stabilization of the conjugate base. However, the electronegativity difference is the primary factor in this comparison.\n\nTherefore, due to chlorine being more electronegative than iodine, HClO4 is a stronger acid than HIO4.",
